Clinical Document

(Document)

Description

Represents a particular health-related document pertaining to a single patient.

Rationale

Allows the capture of patient health data in an encapsulated, contextualized manner with capability of displaying rendered content and communication between simple systems.

Attributes

Document Identifier

(id)

Datatype

SET<II>

Set of Identifier (Unique collection; each occurrence includes id, assigning authority)

Conformance

Required

Implementers must support, but only supply data when it is available

Repetitions

Unlimited

Number of repetitions are unlimited

 

 

 

Description

A globally unique identifier assigned by the EHR to the Clinical Document.

Rationale

Allows for unique identification of the Clinical Document and is therefore mandatory. Supports drill-down queries, linking of this record to other records, matching of EHR records to locally-stored PoS records and is necessary when identifying records for update.

 

Document Category

(code)

Datatype

CD

Complex Code (includes mnemonic, code-system, translations and modifiers)

Conformance

Mandatory

Value must always be supplied (no nulls)

Repetitions

Document Masking Indicators

(confidentialityCode)

Datatype

Repetitions

Unlimited

Code Strength

CNE

Must be coded using 'official' codeset (no un-coded text or local codes)

Code Domain

Confidentiality

 

 

 

Description

Communicates the desire of the patient to restrict access to this Clinical Document record. Provides support for additional confidentiality constraint, giving patients a level of control over their information. Methods for accessing masked event records will be governed by each jurisdiction (e.g. court orders, shared secret/consent, etc.).

Can also be used to communicate that the information is deemed to be sensitive and should not be communicated or exposed to the patient (at least without the guidance of the authoring or other responsible healthcare provider).

Valid values are: 'normal' (denotes 'Not Masked'); 'restricted' (denotes 'Masked') and 'taboo' (denotes 'patient restricted'). The default is 'normal' signifying 'Not Masked'. Either or both of the other codes can be asserted to indicate masking by the patient from providers or masking by a provider from the patient, respectively.

Rationale

Allows the patient to have discrete control over access to their health data. Awareness of the patient's desire for confidentiality is important even for providers who have access to the data because it indicates a need for extra caution before disclosing the information to other care providers.

Also allows providers to mark records as "not for patient display" for circumstances where the patient has access to their own EHR. (There are some pieces of information where it would be detrimental to a patient's health or ongoing care were they to be aware of those records without careful guidance.)

Two repetitions are supported to allow indicating that the record is masked from both a provider and a patient perspective.

The attribute is optional because not all systems will support masking.

Implementation

The value specified for a particular record may be overridden by a higher level masking applied to an indication, a type of data or even all patient records.

Description

Used to identify any records that are "superceded" by the current record. This will cause the referenced records to be marked as "obsolete" with a reference pointing to this record.

Rationale

Used in circumstances where information initially captured about an event is erroneous, incomplete or not captured at the desired level of detail and the change cannot be made by retracting the original record. (E.g. Too much time has elapsed, change is being made by a provider other than the original author of the vent record, etc.) May also be used to reference multiple records in the case where the same event has been accidentally captured more than once.

May also be used when this is a newer "version" of the type of Clinical Document than those records being referenced.

Description

This identifies the person or organization that has primary responsibility for the actions of the author in creating the Clinical Document. The supervising provider is not necessarily present when the action is performed, but is professionally accountable for the action through the power to delegate, and the duty to review actions with the performing actor after the fact.

Rationale

Needed in circumstances where one provider is acting under the professional authority of another. E.g. Pharmacy technician under pharmacist, resident under supervising physician, etc.

Tracking responsibility is essential for authorization and regulatory purposes. It also provides a secondary person to contact for follow-up.

Implementation

If not specified, it is assumed that the author is acting under their own professional authority. I.e. If the author and supervisor are the same, only the author should be sent.

Code Domain

x_ActStatusActiveComplete

 

 

 

Description

This identifies the current state of the Clinical Document.

If the status is 'active' it means the request is still outstanding or in progress. If the status is 'complete' it means that the referral has been acted upon and the referral is considered closed. If the status is 'aborted' it means the request made by the referral has been withdrawn.

Rationale

Status is frequently used to filter query responses as well as to sort records for presentation. It also affects how the Clinical Document record is interpreted. Because the status won't always be known, the attribute is marked as 'populated' to allow the use of null flavors.

It is important to note that the EHR is not expected to perform status management of referrals. Thus it is up to clinicians to amend the status of a referral when it has changed to complete.

Provider Id

(id)

Datatype

SET<II>

Set of Identifier (Unique collection; each occurrence includes id, assigning authority)

Conformance

Optional

Implementers may declare whether they support the concept or not

Repetitions

1

Does not repeat

 

 

 

Description

A unique provider identifier such as the MINC #; (a unique lifetime identifier for physicians in Canada). Other health care professions such as nursing and dietitians have similar identifiers. For those providers (such as family members, friends, neighbors and others who are part of the patient's informal support network will not have identifiers) the system will assign identifiers for the purpose of linking information within the message.

Rationale

An identifier is the best way of kinking a provider to information in a provider registry, and therefore will be required in the absence of a provider name.

Issues

For non-professional providers and others who do not have unique provider numbers, applications must create 'internal' identifiers to allow referencing of the provider within the message.

AssignedEntity

(Author)

Description

This identifies the provider who is responsible for the decision to capture the Clinical Document in the patient's EHR. Note that while the author is frequently the data-enterer, this will not always be the case, for example where transcribers are involved.

Rationale

Used to identify responsibility for accuracy and relevance of the information. This association reflects primary responsibility, and is therefore mandatory.

The author is generally the person to contact with requests for additional information. In some cases, this information may also be used for filtering or sorting.
